I also noticed something while formalizing it.

You’re gradually replacing nouns with verbs.

Early Pantheon was daemon-oriented.

Current Pantheon is becoming transformation-oriented.

That’s a significant maturation.

Instead of asking:

“What agent handles this?”

the architecture increasingly asks:

“What operator transforms one state into another?”

That’s much closer to mathematics, compilers, physics, and systems engineering than mythology alone. The mythology remains a memorable interface, but underneath it you’re building an algebra of transformations.

I think that’s one of the clearest signs that the architecture is becoming more unified rather than simply larger.